segments.text: Let me get through this introduction, then I think we ought to quit.
Sorry.
That's why I went over.
And if we get to drag this out now, we're talking, aren't we?
We'll just edit all of this out.
At that time, I went over there.
The Air Force, the United States Air Force commander at Saigon was called a second air division.
At the time I was going over there, it was changed to 7th Air Force.
A little bit before I went over there, it might have been changed to 7th Air Force.
The 13th Air Force was in the Philippines, and they command administrative-wise, support-wise, 13th Air Force in the Philippines.
Now, we're going to get into complex things, so bear with me.
They owned the fighter units based in Thailand.
Now, I'm not talking about the fighter units in South Vietnam.
That was run by the 2nd Air Division and 7th Air Force.
But the 13th Air Force owned and supported these units in Thailand.
My job was to be in Udorn, the Royal Thai Air Force Base in Udorn, Thailand.
U-D-O-R-N.
We were going to set up a headquarters at the direction of the chief of staff of the Air Force to a great extent for political and Air Force military reasons.
The ranking
United States.
So what we're doing then, there was no base before you went.
Oh yeah, these are Thai Air Force.
Thailand, there was no Americans at the base before you went.
Oh yeah, there was an American unit, a fighter unit.
That had been actually a recon unit there.
But the several other Thailand Air Force bases all belonged to the Royal Thai Air Force.
We had fighter units based there that were doing the bombing against North Vietnam.
And supported by tankers for air refueling from
bases in the Philippines, and Iwo Jima.
Not Iwo Jima.
Okinawa.
Okinawa.
Then we built, while I was over there, that's one of the things that supervised, we built a huge B-52 and tanker base in southern Thailand and called it, oh gee, the name.
But anyway.
I'll think of it.
You're still telling me now why you went over there.
Okay.
These forces were all under 13th Air Force.
Now, the Thailand Command directing the war under General Westmoreland was called United States Command South Vietnam.
There was a United States Command MacThai, United States Military Command Thailand,
U.S. McTighe, in Bangkok, and the Army got this job as a slot, commanded by an Army, United States Army Major General.
They had, the United States Army, had some communications and logistics type forces at Karat Air Force Base.
for munitions.
That's all the army forces that were in Thailand.

Whereas the United States Air Force had fighter units, F-4s and F-105s at Karat, Ubon, Udorn, and eventually at Nakhon Pathom, had a reconnaissance unit at Udorn, and so-called beret forces, special forces,
at Nakhon Phanom.
A hundred times more units and forces than the United States Army.
Yet, the command slot in Thailand was given to the United States Army.
Any time any politicians or anybody came to Thailand, actually the Army component commander with his army hat on would go down and beat them.
you know, this jealousy.
Sure.
Inter-service rivalry.
Inter-service rivalry that was just unacceptable as far as the Air Force was concerned.
So... Too much rivalry as far as the Air Force... Well, I mean, it was unacceptable.
The fact that this man was arming...
It was disproportionate command and responsibility-wise on the spot.
The general commanding McIntyre forces was...
Of course, he assumed that he'd had response below the other forces, too, and acted as though he'd command them, and that irritated him.
So there's a lot of friction between the Army general and the Air Force general in Thailand.
There was no Air Force general in Thailand.
No, not until I got there.
That's what I'm explaining.
That's the reason the position was set up by General McConnell, Chief of Staff, and the ambassador of
Thailand fully endorsed this.
And so did the ambassador at Laos, Ambassador Graham Martin in Thailand, Ambassador I've already given you his name before.

Anyway, they set up and they sent me, and matter of fact, I was personally briefed by General McConnell, the Chief of Staff of the Air Force, in his office before I went as to really what my job was to be in very general terms.
Essentially, I was to represent the Air Force in Thailand, and I ranked.
the Army general in charge of MACTI by about a year.
And, you know, in services rank has its privileges and also there's a special regulation in the armed forces where a commander junior to a subordinate cannot command him.
Word to this effect.
I was sent over as the, my job, my title was to be Deputy Commander 7th Air Force Headquarters.
I had five bosses.
The Commander 7th Air Force in Saigon was my boss from the standpoint of tactical coordination, where he expected me on the spot for all the fighter forces, and if you will, air defense also.
We had radar sites manned.

by Air Force people with the Thai people working with Thailand, but from a strictly Air Force standpoint, the United States Air Force Department, the Command 7th Air Force, and wrote his OER on me, Officer Fechner's report on my performance, in support of coordinating on a tactical effort.
He wrote the FRAG orders.
Okay, so he was your first boss.
That's my first boss.
was the commander of 13th Air Force of the Philippines because he owned and logistically supported all of this Thailand operation of the United States Air Force.
And I was on the spot commander in implementing all of that responsibility and, you know, inspection, supervision, and saying that it was done and all.
My united, my joint commander,
was General Stilwell, the Commander Bactai, United States Commander, Military Air Command, Thailand.
And the Joint Command, Chain of Command, he was to be my commander, but I ranked him.

The minute he learned about me coming over there, even before I left the United States, he sent a wire through Army Channel, and it hit Washington, D.C., and he wanted to know why this was being done.
General McConnell told me about this before he even left, and I sort of managed it.
And he, you know, indicated to me the problem I was going to have, but I think you're capable of handling it.
I want the United States Air Force represented in Thailand, and you're the man I'm sending over there to do it.
When people come over there and land in Bangkok, no matter where they always land, you beat them.
Yes, sir.
I knew what he was getting at.
I'd have been trained.
Now, I've talked about three bosses.
Now, it might surprise you to say- What did the Army say, though, when they received this telegram?
They couldn't do anything about it.
They couldn't do anything about it.
This was a United States Air Force administrative action.
Okay, so you're fourth boss.
Fourth boss.
Right.
My fourth and fifth bosses were ambassadors.
And they acted like it.
Grant Martin, and I got along with both of them beautifully, but I must admit when I talked to some of my military bosses, I got my head beat in and it was a problem.
But before we get to Graham Martin, we're going to talk about him.
So you have five bosses, and your job, regardless of your title here, which is somewhat confusing, your job was that you were the senior Air Force officer in Thailand.
On the spot in Thailand.
Representing the Air Force.
In other words, you were the senior Air Force commander in Thailand.
I was a senior United States military commander in Thailand.
Yeah, right.
Because you outranked your so-called boss.
And immediately, of course, this gave the McTighe commander, an Army general, room to ask for his third star.
And what was his name?
General Stilwell.
He and I got along all right.
He and I knew what was going on.
And we, you know, sometimes just have to accept the situation and we got along all right.
So you had no problems with him really?
Oh yeah, we had problems.
At times we even had a few words, but we glossed over them and we got along all right.
I have a great respect for him and I think he had great respect for me.
I hope.
But Graham Martin was the ambassador of Thailand was in effect
He sort of acted as a boss in a way, politically and diplomatically, and also across the border was Ambassador Bill Sullivan.
Okay, Bill Sullivan.
Bill Sullivan was Ambassador to Laos.
Young, very ambitious, and very capable ambassador.
And I found out that even he and Graham Martin, you know, had their differences.
In a diplomatic world, just like in a military world, you know, you have
people jealous of their prerogatives and so forth.
Can you imagine my position?
Five bosses.
I am sure that, looking over my records, based on the best jobs I had, that that's the reason General McConnell
A terrific guy, by the way, Chief of Staff.
That's the reason he gave me that job.
And to make a long story short, when I left he rewarded me for the job I did and gave me commander of a technical air force, the 12th Air Force.
But this was an interesting tour and I would suggest what we do now is sort of break it down.
OK. You talked about your five boss.
Oh, I should say that this is the 23rd of January, 1981.
And this is our third day of interview.
Now, you talked yesterday afternoon about your five bosses.
I'd like to know about your command at Udorn and how many airplanes we have there.
What was the mission, the function of the Air Force in Thailand?

I guess the best way to describe it is that I have to start with the commander of the entire Southeast Asian war at that time, General Westmoreland, commander of the entire American forces, Army, Navy, and Air Force in the area, reporting straight back to the front chiefs of staff.
But under him, of course, you had the Air Force component,
the 7th Air Force, which did the air action for the Southeast Asian operation, but I hasten to add, did not control entirely naval air, which is a point that I think we'll get into later on.
But we attempted many times to get control of naval air, particularly under General Momar when I was over there.
But under the 7th Air Force,
We had air forces in South Vietnam, of course.

But for the major efforts in striking North Vietnam, in bombing, if you will, all done by fighters, these forces were based at several bases in Thailand and were, to use the vernacular of the military, frag, fragmentation orders, written, ordering them on certain flights the following day.
All of this was fragged from 7th Air Force.
Now the logistical support for all these forces in Thailand, fighters and bombers, fighters and tankers, and eventually B-52s, were from the 13th Air Force based in the Philippines.
Well, Clark Air Force Base.
It's just the peculiarities of organization in the Southeast Asian area.
Logistical support came from 13th Air Force responsibility.
Operational control and fighting the war actually from 7th Air Force in Saigon.
7th Air Force being a four-star general, General Mollmeyer at the time.
13th Air Force being Lieutenant General Jim Wilson at the time.
How do you spell Mollmeyer?
M-O-M-M-Y-E-R.
classmate of mine.
Terrific, terrific man.
Very controversial, by the way, too, but terrific.
The fighter forces based at the several bases in Thailand, Ubon, Udorn, Korat, Takli, and minor forces at the Khan Phanom, if you will,
the reconnaissance forces based at Boudourne, and the huge tankers and eventually B-52s based at the huge base we built during the time I was over there.
And I've got to get the name of this base for you.
I'll probably think of it before the discussion is over.
These actions were controlled primarily by the 7th Air Force, but I also haste to add, this gets complicated,

control or both operational and support supply came over the both the tankers and the b-52s came down eventually from sac headquarters through his various sub commands and chain of command through okinawa to these forces based in thailand
is SAC controlled forces.

And here again, SAC would never give up complete control of these forces to even the 7th Air Force commander, much less the 13th Air Force, and much less the unified commander, General Westmoreland of Southeast Asia.
SAC retained control of these forces.
He couldn't?
Westmoreland couldn't get that control away?
Westmoreland requested, Westmoreland always requested this support, but of course he got it from SAC.
You remember, you've read about the huge bombings, the carpet bombing types, the B-52s.
Right.
General Westmoreland, as the unified commander for all armed forces in the United States and Southeast Asia, he requested these types of strikes in coordination, really, with SAC planners.
But he didn't order them.
But he didn't.
Well, let's say he requested them and Sack fulfilled them.

These, of course, were coordinated really through Seventh Air Force because the number one air component, the number one air commander, and this was basic concepts of Air Force doctrine, and even Sack admitted this, that there had to be a single air commander
in any theater, and that was essentially General Volmeyer.

But let's say sometimes this was kind of blinked at at SAC, because after all, you know, we had SAC, and give them credit, they had to retain control of their forces in case of, let's say, a big breakout someplace else.
And remember, these B-52s were being utilized over there, also had a nuclear capability.
So they had to be, he had to be free to be able to pull his forces out at any time.
He recognized the requirements of Southeast Station Bar and General Westmoreland's requirements, and the Air Force Component Commander, General Mobar, 7th Air Force.
He recognized their requirements.
But it was a matter of very, sometimes very complicated coordination, but it got done.
And the strikes, bomber strikes in North Vietnam, were effective.
I say effective.
But we'll get to that.
OK.
It was a tough task.
Now, that's the way we operated.
Now, my job specifically in Thailand was, as I described to think earlier, was the on-the-spot Air Force commander.
It was far, far more politically than it was tactically.
Sounds like it.
Really, support-wise, because support, coordination, and planning went directly from 13th Air Force Headquarters, really to the bases.
I, if you will, was an explorer, was an on-the-spot implementer, was an on-the-spot supervisor, and I put out the fires if I had a problem.
I was on the spot in Thailand.
I got the information.
I called General Wilson on the telephone and said, we've got to do this and do that.
I was a... You kept the Air Force running smoothly in Thailand.
I coordinated problems.
And coordinating problems between five bosses is a difficult problem, to say the least.
As a matter of fact, you might mention at this time, as typical of my job,
It was a tough job.
I wrote a letter to General McConnell after I'd been over there about two or three months.
I wrote a letter to him because he said, sometime now, if you're over there, let me know.
Write me and let me know how you're doing and what the problems are.
So I wrote him a letter.
It took two or three days, but I wrote it carefully.
But one of my comments in the letter was that you told me to use my head.
I assure you I have used my head, and I've got a lot of knots on it.
Fortunately, I still have it on my shoulders.
Then I explained why, coordination between five bosses.
And I knew he'd get kicked out of it.
As a matter of fact, I found out later on, Butch, his deputy chief of staff, I mean his vice chief of staff at the Air Force, a SAC man, Butch, I think the name made it wrong.
He visited over there and told me, he said, Charlie, you know the letter you wrote to General McConnell?
I said, yeah.
He said, one day, one morning at staff meeting, he brought that letter to the staff meeting of his entire staff and read that part about your head.
And he said, I'm telling you, it cracked up the entire staff.
He said, they've never earned anything for money in their life because they knew exactly, they knew exactly what I was talking about.
They knew General Jim Wilson, who was called the alligator.
They knew General Momar.
grim, tough, so-and-so.
They knew General Stilwell, died in the World Army guy, and definitely for the Army, and right in the middle of this problem of the controversy between Army and Air Force.
They knew Graham Martin, the ambassador, and they knew little Bill Sullivan, the very aggressive little ambassador of Laos.
They knew exactly what my problem was.
So General McConnell got quite a kick out of it.
But that exemplifies and explains as an example of really what my job was.
I coordinated.

Besides the coordination, which is always a headache, I would imagine, were there other problems that you had to deal with, let's say, as far as keeping equipment maintained or as far as personnel, maybe drugs or I don't know, anything to do, any problems that you had as far as maintenance and personnel and just
living in Thailand and keeping the Thais and the American airmen good relations, any of those things?
Oh yeah, there's numerous.
There were numerous problems and they varied from day to day.
I might add also, in a way you might say I had a sixth boss, but I never really concerned myself too much about it, but this was the chief of staff of the Thai Air Forces.
See all these were Thai, T-H-A-I, Thailand.
All these were Thai bases.
We never took them over.
We just used them.
And thank goodness we had that concrete in Thailand.
Otherwise, we'd never been able to get fighters up to bomb North Vietnam.
I can't remember any great problem about shortages.
We violated many, many Air Force regulations strictly about building budgets-wise and dollars.
Goodness, the way we had to build bases over there.
We had to do it.
I gave General Wilson credit.
Matter of fact, I take my hat off to him.
He didn't let written regulations stop him.
If we needed this base and we needed something on it, he said build it.
For example?
What type of rules and regulations?
Well, you have to get, let's say, certain approval of a certain amount of money
for a certain project normally in the United States before you can do anything?
And do you have the budget money?
Were you within the budget to do it?
And a commander of an air force had to sign off on a particular thing before even the staff could proceed, give the base authority to do it.
Of course, we're in a war.
Jim didn't worry about these things.
General Wilson didn't worry about it.
I didn't worry about it.
But sometimes when the staff or inspectors from Pentagon come down through there, well, you know, they'd come to the surface and there'd be problems.
You had to...
talk about.
Morale problems amongst the THUD drivers, if you will, the F-105 aircraft.
You know, we were losing pilots.
Never before, never before has air attacks been made in such dense, modern surface-to-air missile defenses as was done by Seventh Air Force fighters.
against North Vietnam.
These were Soviet-installed, Soviet-made, Soviet-installed SAMs, and they were effective.
And we lost pilots.
We lost aircraft to those things.
We devised tactics to get around it.
It's just typical of any other thing.
When you come up against advanced technology, you devise a tactic.
Or more technology,
How many pilots do you remember?
Do you remember how many you lost, and what type were the tactics?
How did you get around the SAMs?
How successful were your tactics?
We were successful in getting around them.
One of General Momar's problems as an Air Force commander was, and I take my hat off to him, should I concentrate on still tending my attacking forces against the target, namely, let's say,
an air base where fighters are, a power plant.
Should I, right in the middle of a missile defense in Hanoi, should I continue to do that?
Or since I'm losing aircraft at almost an unacceptable rate, should I maybe divert some action against these missile defenses first and then hit my targets?
Well, he stuck to his job.
He continued
to hit the targets and bomb them, because we knew we could always get through any defenses.
But remember, this was the first time we came up against modern surface-to-air missiles.
So we had to devise tactics, and we devised First, how many did you lose?
What at times, let's say, Karat would come back with a force of maybe 25 F-105s.
of their base, 24 F-105 from their base, took off and attacked and come back and five aircraft and five pilots would be missing that morning.
No kidding.
You could lose 25% or 20% in just one raid?
Yep.
That afternoon, let's say maybe we lose three more at one base.
This affected pilot more.
No kidding.
The F-105s took the brunt.
Those aircraft

When you'd see them take off with as much as 16 bombs hanging underneath the fighter, saying that they could go Mach 1, in other words, at the speed of sound, carrying these bombs, they did well to climb to 20,000 feet with that bomb load on them.
Sure.
The escorting F-4s had to throttle back to stay with them.
not escorting, but I mean flying with them because they had better performance.
They had to be refueled for just that flight up to North Vietnam.
By tankers, absolutely.
They couldn't make it because they carried so many bombs.
But it was this type of thing.
But to get around these SAMs was another thing.
Okay, now let's talk about that.
Well, we devised, what's the word we used?
I'll have to fill this in for you.

But it was a flight and special-designed F-105s, two-seater F-105s, where you had an operator in the back looking at instrumentation that had been installed in the aircraft to pick up the launching of a SAM and actually have a strobe to point where it was coming from.
And then having found out where it was coming from, then the aircraft would launch a special mission, a special missile
air-to-ground missile called ahere it is.
I can't remember.
I have to get the name of that.
You've got me going here.
I'll fill in as we get back.
And he had launched this missile, air-to-ground missile, against the SAM site.
In other words, we suppress the SAMs.
At the same time, the bombers are coming over to drop their bombs.
Okay, so I'm a little lost here.
How did you know the Sands were there?
They'd shoot at you.
Okay, but I mean, what you do is sort of, this is not very military language, but what you do is sort of send a decoy over?
No, our bombers, gradually, as our bombers were bombing Hanoi, they had to do something in Hanoi to defend.
Their MiGs couldn't defend against it.
Therefore, the Soviets gave them these missiles, advanced technology.
We didn't know this at first.
Well, gee, come back, you critique.
Golly, this missile came by me, and I saw it actually launch to the ground.
Okay, you build up intelligence.
It's SAMs.
These are new things.
More of them appeared.
We started losing pilots.
We've got to do something about this.
So you've pinpointed on a map where the SAMs were installed.
You always maintain your order of battle.
You know exactly where they are.
Okay, and so then you'd send in a first strike against the SAMs specifically, try to wipe them out, and then your bombers would go in right after that.
Is that true?
Yes, this is partially true.
Okay, well, explain it to me exactly true.
Okay, in addition, well...
As the bombers go in, the fighter bombers, just preceding their strike is this flight of either two or four F-105, either to actually strike the SAM sites when they come up.
See, they have to turn on their radars.
When they turn on their radars to pick up our incoming bombers, that's when we can pick them up electronically and our instruments can point them.
And we can fire the missiles out of them.
They know this.
And they know when we pick them up by our instrumentation, by their electronic pickups.
So they have got to decide, am I going to turn my SAM radar equipment on in order to fire my SAMs and get this incoming missile from them and knock me out?
Or am I going to, am I going to suffer that loss?
Or should I
keep my radars off and not use my SAMs.
So it's ECM, electromagnetic warfare.
We suppressed the SAMs with this flight of, I got to think of the name we called it, and we had special trained pilots to fly this.
Boy, this was a nerve-wracking flight.
Very nerve-wracking.
And these boys got medals one right after another.

But at least they could identify the missiles and know when they're being fired, whereas the bomber boys flying the bomber strike fighters, they might visually see a missile launch, going and see the...
But they didn't have an electronic tool?
No, but they could...
The way the fighter bomber boys knew whether a missile was coming after them, if they could see the smoke from the...
smoke trail of the missile, they knew it wasn't going to hit them.
And by the way, they called them telephone poles.
That's about the way they looked when they passed by and missed you.
Looked like a telephone pole.
Long, slim thing.
You've seen pictures of it.
But if you couldn't see them, the smoke trail behind them, that's pretty well, they were coming in your direction.
Now, evasive tactics, and this was a problem.
And rightfully so.
If too many of these things were coming up at you, the air commander would make the decision to drop your bombs and take your bases back.
In other words, save the airplane and save your, you know what, get back so we can come up again, and immediately dive.
Turn and dive.
So you dive down?
Yeah, dive down.
Into them?
Well, dive down, because that's going to bury the...

closing rate of the missile against you and also you're going to turn which means that the missile has to to take action the guy to get to you but it also changes the closing rate of the missile and therefore it explode above you probably when you do that and this was the famous favorite survival tactic turn and dive drop your bombs and when you've done that of course then
You've got all the garbage off the bottom of your airplane and going to afterburner up to around Mach 1 because you're at low altitude, and you've got to get up to speed, otherwise MIGs catch you.
See, the MIGs also in this that you're confined with, along with the SAM missiles.
This gets complicated, and it gets ticklish, and it's tough, tough.
And this is a problem we were confined with over there.
Now, what about us?
Let's move back just a second here, and this concerns the North Vietnamese.
If we were having electronic warfare, and as soon as they turn their radar on, we could pick them up and try to shoot an air-to-surface missile into them.
Surface to air?
No, from our airplane.
I'm sorry, air-to-surface.
If we could try to do that, would they set up
dummy radar stations?
Well, see, that's ECM for you.
They could, and probably did, set up some dummy stations.
However... And that was on, and that hit you on the other one?
Well, now, it just takes a while to explain all that.
Now, in addition, in addition over there, we had what were called ECM aircraft.
This is another element of air power.
We had deployed Carat Air Force Base, Tockley Air Force Base.

They were B-66 type aircraft, a twin-engine jet that had special electronic equipment on it for picking up any radar, any electronic mission that you might have, radar, radio, you name it, in North Vietnam, as well as these SAMs.
And also, they had jamming equipment in them.
Now, this aircraft flew in coordination with the airstrikes.
And they flew generally at the periphery, around the periphery of the area.
Plus the fact that they had to be protected to a certain extent sometimes by escort.
We lost a few of these aircraft.
And you see, when they have their jamming equipment on, this is a perfect target for a SAM.
the SAM can home on that jamming equipment.
However, if they're jamming the frequency of the SAM, then ain't no way that SAM is going to be able to hit them because he can't home on them.
His direction radar and direction communication equipment is jammed.
It's useless.
In other words, you jam his guiding equipment.
Of course, the ideal thing is to have these, and I can't think of the name, and I'll still have to go in.
These, I thought of one of the names.
The Shrike was the missile.
How do you spell that?
S-H-R-I-K-E.
The Shrike was the missile, air to surface missile, that was carried by these specially equipped F-105 aircraft from Takli and Karat that
launched this missile against the SAM sites.
The threat of this aircraft, just by its way it flew, altitude, tactics and all, the North Vietnamese radar at their SAM site, they eventually could pick up and knew exactly what this flight was.
They knew it and could identify it.
And a lot of times we found they chose to stay off the air.
They wouldn't even fire up their radar for their SAM
sites.
Well, we achieved success by just suppressing them that way.
Suppressed them.
They didn't choose to fire up because they knew that they'd have a missile launched against them.
The most fatal thing in the world they could do was fire up and try to fire a missile against one of these some aircraft that was carrying a Shrike missile

and stay that way, fired up with all their equipment on, then when we launched the strike missile, the strike missile would home in and hit their particular radar site, their particular SAM site, and destroy them.
Of course, destroy the guiding equipment, radar and all, and of course, when we do that, we didn't care whether it destroyed the missile enough because he couldn't fire it.
But, and it got to be a cat and mouse game.
They'd go on and off the air.
But the fact that they knew we had these X-type missiles, X-type aircraft up there, this was a suppression in itself.
Just the threat of launching a missile was a threat.
Now, if you recall in the later years of the war, where the B-52s finally were laid on for mass strikes against North Vietnam, the first requirement ahead of those B-52s
was a full force of these special equipped F-105 strike loaded aircraft to hit them.
And that's one reason we didn't lose hardly any B-52.
Now, you said that after evasive action, as far as the missiles were concerned,
Then you had to worry about the MiGs.
Not after, during the same time.
Okay, during the same time.
How good were these MiGs compared to our aircraft?
Were they the MiG-19s or the 21s?
Oh, no, MiG-21s, some of the latest aircraft.
How good were the 21s?
The MiG-21 was a good airplane.
As a matter of fact, it shot some of our boys down.
The F-4...
was a good match for it.
The F-105 was not so much, it wasn't as capable against the MiG as the F-4 was.
We learned a lot about the MiG-21.
For instance, I told you previously that the evasive tactics for the F-105 against not only the missiles, but the MiGs as well, if they were jumped.
And remember they loaded with bombs.
There's no way they could fight a fighter
to drop the bombs and then die.
We learned through intelligence that the MiG-21, at a certain speed up toward Mach 1, it was very hard to control.
The controls got stiff and almost froze.
We learned that.
And that's one of the reasons the idea was- Was it a slower speed?
It was time to control?
Slower than Mach 1.
Yeah.
That's the reason the F-105 pilots wanted to get to Mach 1 as fast as possible, diving and full afterburner.
And then actually go out on the surface of the ground, going above the speed of sound.
